>>41597131
>How do I get back into it?
There isn’t really any magic solution to getting back into writing. Just have discipline or wait until you’re in the mood, I guess. The way I got past my lack of motivation a few months ago was getting a laptop, which made writing much easier for me. Prior to that, I only had my phone and a crusty PC.

> How do you structure the outline to your story?
Depends. Sometimes I just wing it, other times I make an outline. The ones I do are usually not too complicated, at most it’ll be a basic run through of the plot and small descriptions of the characters and setting(s).

Bed-Man Sun 12 Sep 2021 23:45:27 No.41597708 Report
Quoted By: >>41597857 >>41598211
>>41597131
>How do I get back into it?
Unironically just do it. It'll be hard, but you'll get into the flow of it soon, and then it won't feel like such a big deal.
>How do you structure the outline to your story?
I typically do bullet point lists of major story beats, and then imagine a few possible ways those in-between moments happen to connect the bullet points. I also have a separate doc for little notes. Stuff like brief descriptions of places, people, events, etc, so I can go back and look to see if I'm keeping everything in line, or if there's anything I need to add or change to, for example, make some kind of decent foreshadowing or set up a callback in the future.

Anonymous Sun 12 Sep 2021 23:56:18 No.41597985 Report
Quoted By: >>41598300
>>41597131
In what I call Bones, Flesh, Blood. Sounds grim, but its so things can "grow" as they change.

Start with bones, just the general shape of the story as you intend to go about it, characters, plot points, and other such. Some bones grow and fuse as you refine it more.

Then comes flesh, which is the story of individual arcs, how it affects the characters and how they change from arc to arc.

Then comes blood which flows between the flesh and bones. This is stuff like dialogue, where it just kind of flows.
Anonymous

>>41597708
>I typically do bullet point lists of major story beats
Kind of the same.
Longer stories get a massive continuity file, and the more complicated the plot the longer it gets per scene.
I work backward from overall chapters, add scenes as needed, and worry about minor beat stuff dead last. Somewhere in the middle to end of the first draft the structure starts clicking, and then it's all linking things up.
